<ArticleLayout
  title="Newborn Essentials for New Parents"
  description="A practical Australian guide to the items that tend to matter most in the first few months, with notes on what can wait."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="6 minute read"
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery room with timber furniture, soft lighting and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    Preparing for a newborn can feel like being handed a very long list at the exact moment
    your brain would prefer a cup of tea and a lie down. Strip it back to safe sleep, feeding,
    nappies, washing, transport and a few comfortable clothes.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is not a checklist to finish in one weekend. It separates what you will need early
    from the things that can wait, so the nursery is not full before the baby arrives and the
    household has room to adjust once the routine becomes real.
  </p>

  <h2>The first things to sort out</h2>
  <div class="grid two">
    <ProductCard
      label="Sleep"
      title="A safe sleep space"
      description="Choose a cot or bassinet that suits your room, has a firm mattress and uses fitted sheets made for that exact size."
      note="Keep pillows, loose blankets and decorative soft items out of the sleep space."
    />
    <ProductCard
      label="Changing"
      title="Nappies and a practical change setup"
      description="Choose a change table, mat or floor setup that can be used according to its instructions while supplies remain within adult reach."
    />
    <ProductCard
      label="Clothing"
      title="Simple layers"
      description="Zip suits, singlets, socks and layers for the season are usually easier than fussy outfits in the early weeks."
    />
    <ProductCard
      label="Outings"
      title="A way to travel safely"
      description="Plan for a correctly fitted car restraint and a pram or carrier that suits your home, transport and local footpaths."
    />
  </div>

  <h2>Do not buy for routines you have not met yet</h2>
  <p>
    Monitors, bottle warmers, wipe warmers, large toy collections and specialist organisers may
    become useful, but they are rarely the difference between prepared and unprepared. Decorative
    soft items do not belong in the baby's sleep space.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you are considering a monitor, compare whether you need audio, video or app access,
    and check camera placement, cord safety, range, battery life and privacy settings.
  </p>

  <h2>Compare the items that change the room</h2>
  <ComparisonTable rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2>Plan for the weather and the room you have</h2>
  <p>
    Think about summer heat, winter room temperature, rental limitations, storage space and
    how often you will need to move items between rooms. A compact, washable setup can be
    more useful than a nursery arranged for a photo but awkward to use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Buy only a small group of clothes that fit now and suit the season. Feeding supplies should
    match the approach you plan to begin with while leaving room to change after advice or
    experience. Bath items need somewhere to dry; nappies and wipes need a restock point rather
    than an entire cupboard beside the change mat.
  </p>

  <h2>Second-hand is an item-by-item decision</h2>
  <p>
    Used clothing, washable storage and some furniture may be reasonable when their condition is
    clear. Safety-sensitive products need a stricter check. Avoid anything with missing labels or
    instructions, an unknown history, damage, incomplete parts or an unresolved recall.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume that a hand-me-down mattress fits a different cot or bassinet, or that an older
    restraint remains suitable because it looks intact. Check the exact product, its history and
    the current guidance for that category.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the first list short</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Safe sleep space, fitted sheets and sleepwear suited to the season.</li>
    <li>Nappies, wipes, barrier cream if used and a suitable changing setup.</li>
    <li>Several outfits that are easy to change and fit now.</li>
    <li>Feeding supplies that match your planned approach, with room to adjust later.</li>
    <li>Baby bath basics, soft towels and gentle laundry planning.</li>
    <li>Correctly fitted car restraint before the first trip home.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Use current Australian guidance for the safety decisions</h2>
  <p>
    For sleep, start with{" "}
    <ExternalLink href="https://rednose.org.au/safe-sleep-and-safer-pregnancy/overview/">Red Nose safe sleep advice</ExternalLink>{" "}
    and the specific <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/settle-baby-to-sleep-safely/bassinets-and-cradles-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Product Safety bassinets and cradles guide</a>.
    The broader <ExternalLink href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/">Product Safety Australia website</ExternalLink>{" "}
    carries product guidance and recall information, including specific{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/bathe-and-change-baby-safely" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">bathing and changing advice</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Use <ExternalLink href="https://www.childcarseats.com.au/">Child Car Seats Australia</ExternalLink>{" "}
    when comparing restraints and fitting information. Read these sources alongside product
    instructions and qualified professional advice where relevant. The detailed
    <a href="https://rednose.org.au/resources/safe-sleeping/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Red Nose safe sleeping guide</a>{" "}
    sets out the current recommendations for babies aged 0–12 months.
  </p>

  <h2>Leave room for the baby to change the list</h2>
  <p>
    Prepare the safety and care basics, but keep receipts, packaging and spare space where
    practical. The first weeks will show which clothes are easiest, where changes happen and which
    feeding or bath supplies are genuinely useful. That information is worth more than completing
    a generic newborn list before the baby arrives.
  </p>

  <FAQBlock items={faqs} />
  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
